# Plan: Add `mistral-instruct-v3` Chat Template Handler

## Context

Mistral Instruct v0.3 is the classic Mistral chat format (exemplified by
`mistralai-Mistral-Nemo-Instruct-2407.jinja`). It wraps every user turn in
`[INST]…[/INST]` delimiters, prepends any system message to the **first** user
turn (not the last), and appends the eos token (`</s>`) after every assistant
turn.  Templates matching this pattern currently fall through to the differential
autoparser because no specialized handler claims them.  The new handler provides
explicit, deterministic handling with a clean PEG content parser — without
touching any existing handlers or the header file.

---

## Only file modified

```
common/chat.cpp
```

No other files change (header file and all existing handlers are untouched).

---

## Step 1 – Add handler function (insert after line 940)

Insert the new function between the closing `}` of
`common_chat_params_init_ministral_3` (line 940) and the opening line of
`common_chat_params_init_gpt_oss` (line 942).

```cpp
static common_chat_params common_chat_params_init_mistral_instruct_v3(
    const common_chat_template &          tmpl,
    const autoparser::generation_params & inputs) {
    common_chat_params data;

    // Mistral Instruct v0.3 prepends the system message to the *first* user
    // turn rather than keeping it as a separate message.
    auto        adjusted_messages = json::array();
    std::string system_content;
    bool        has_system = false;

    for (const auto & msg : inputs.messages) {
        if (!has_system && msg.value("role", "") == "system") {
            has_system = true;
            if (msg.contains("content") && msg.at("content").is_string()) {
                system_content = msg.at("content").get<std::string>();
            }
            continue;  // drop standalone system message; will be inlined below
        }
        adjusted_messages.push_back(msg);
    }

    // Prepend system content to the first user turn
    if (has_system && !system_content.empty()) {
        for (auto & msg : adjusted_messages) {
            if (msg.value("role", "") == "user" && msg.contains("content") &&
                msg.at("content").is_string()) {
                msg["content"] =
                    system_content + "\n\n" + msg.at("content").get<std::string>();
                break;
            }
        }
    }

    data.prompt = common_chat_template_direct_apply_impl(
        tmpl, inputs, /* messages_override = */ adjusted_messages);
    data.format = COMMON_CHAT_FORMAT_PEG_NATIVE;

    auto parser = build_chat_peg_parser([&](common_chat_peg_builder & p) {
        return p.prefix(inputs.generation_prompt) << p.content(p.rest());
    });
    data.parser = parser.save();

    return data;
}
```

**Key decisions:**
- `common_chat_template_direct_apply_impl` (declared at line 767) is reused
  exactly as the Ministral 3 handler uses it, passing `adjusted_messages` as
  the override.
- `build_chat_peg_parser` / `p.prefix` / `p.content` / `p.rest()` follow the
  same pattern as the `force_pure_content` path at line 1774 — the simplest
  valid parser.
- `p.prefix(inputs.generation_prompt)` uses the default empty delimiter (see
  `chat-peg-parser.h` line 96: `delimiter = {}`).
- No `supports_thinking`, no `preserved_tokens`, no grammar — the format has
  none of those.

---

